INSERT INTO public.blog_posts (title, slug, excerpt, content, category_id, published, published_at, updated_at)
VALUES (
  'Laptop Keyboard Not Working? Try These 11 Fixes',
  'laptop-keyboard-not-working',
  'Laptop keyboard not working on Windows 11 or Windows 10? Try these 11 practical fixes to solve keyboard issues, unresponsive keys, typing errors, driver problems, and settings issues.',
  E'If your laptop keyboard is not working, you are not alone. A laptop keyboard can suddenly stop typing, some keys may stop responding, or the keyboard may type the wrong letters or symbols.\n\nThe good news is that most keyboard problems are caused by settings, dust, driver issues, or layout problems rather than full hardware failure. In this guide, you will learn exactly how to fix a laptop keyboard that is not working on Windows 11 or Windows 10.\n\n## Quick Fixes to Try First\n\nIf you need a fast fix, start with these steps before moving into the full troubleshooting guide.\n\n- Restart your laptop.\n- Run a [keyboard test](/test/keyboard) online.\n- Clean the keyboard gently.\n- Check if Filter Keys is turned on.\n- Make sure the correct keyboard layout is selected.\n- Update or reinstall the keyboard driver.\n- Test with an external keyboard.\n\n## Why Your Laptop Keyboard Is Not Working\n\nA laptop keyboard can stop working for several reasons. In most cases, the problem is caused by a software or settings issue rather than a broken keyboard.\n\n- Dust or dirt is stuck under the keys.\n- The keyboard driver is outdated, missing, or corrupted.\n- The wrong keyboard layout is selected.\n- Filter Keys or another accessibility setting is affecting typing.\n- A recent Windows update caused a temporary issue.\n- The function keys are in the wrong mode.\n- The built-in keyboard has physical damage.\n- The keyboard cable or internal hardware has failed.\n\n## 11 Ways to Fix a Laptop Keyboard That Is Not Working\n\n### Fix 1: Restart Your Laptop\n\nA restart can fix temporary system glitches and reload the keyboard driver. Click Start, select Power, and choose Restart. After the laptop turns back on, test the keyboard again.\n\n### Fix 2: Run an Online Keyboard Test\n\nBefore guessing, test the keys.\n\nOpen LaptopAnalyzer''s [keyboard test](/test/keyboard) and press each key one by one. This helps you see whether:\n\n- One or two keys are not working\n- Many keys are not working\n- The full keyboard has stopped responding\n\nIf you want to check more than just the keyboard, use the [full laptop test](/test/full) on LaptopAnalyzer. It runs the hardware tests one by one in a single flow, so users do not need to open every tool manually.\n\n### Fix 3: Clean the Keyboard Gently\n\nTurn off the laptop first.\n\nThen:\n\n- Wipe the keyboard with a soft, dry cloth\n- Use compressed air between the keys\n- Check for stuck, loose, or damaged keys\n\nDo not spray liquid directly onto the keyboard.\n\n### Fix 4: Disconnect Extra Devices\n\nRemove USB devices, hubs, docking stations, and external keyboards. Then restart the laptop and test the built-in keyboard again. Sometimes another device or connection can cause input issues.\n\n### Fix 5: Use the On-Screen Keyboard\n\nIf you need to type while fixing the problem, turn on the [Windows on-screen keyboard](https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/use-the-on-screen-keyboard-osk-to-type-ecbb5e08-5b4e-d8c8-f794-81dbf896267a). This helps you log in, search settings, and continue troubleshooting even if the physical keyboard is not typing.\n\n### Fix 6: Test With an External Keyboard\n\nConnect a USB or wireless keyboard.\n\nThis tells you a lot:\n\n- If the external keyboard works, the problem is likely with the built-in laptop keyboard.\n- If the external keyboard also does not work, the issue may be deeper in Windows or the system itself.\n\n### Fix 7: Check the Keyboard Layout\n\nIf your laptop keyboard is typing wrong letters or symbols, the layout may have changed.\n\nOpen your language and keyboard settings and make sure the correct layout is selected. This is a very common reason for typing problems when the keyboard hardware is actually fine.\n\n### Fix 8: Turn Off Filter Keys\n\nIf the keyboard feels slow, skips letters, or ignores quick key presses, Filter Keys may be turned on.\n\nTurn it off in Windows accessibility settings and test the keyboard again.\n\n### Fix 9: Update Windows\n\nInstall any pending Windows updates and restart the laptop. Some keyboard issues happen after a partial update and are fixed after the full update is complete.\n\n### Fix 10: Reinstall the Keyboard Driver\n\nOpen Device Manager, find the keyboard, right-click it, and choose Uninstall device. Then restart the laptop. Windows usually installs the keyboard driver again automatically.\n\nIf needed, you can also choose Update driver first and let Windows search for the latest version.\n\n### Fix 11: Check for Physical Damage\n\nIf the keyboard problem started after a spill, drop, strong pressure, or long-term wear, the issue may be hardware-related.\n\nCommon signs include:\n\n- The same keys always fail\n- Keys feel sticky or loose\n- The keyboard does not work even after the driver fixes\n- The built-in keyboard fails, but an external keyboard works\n\nAt that point, repair or replacement may be needed.\n\n## Some Laptop Keys Not Working\n\nIf only a few keys are not working, start with this order:\n\n- Run an online [keyboard test](/test/keyboard)\n- Clean the keyboard carefully\n- Test the same keys again\n- Check for stuck or loose keys\n- Try an external keyboard\n\nWhen the same few keys always fail, the problem is often physical, not software.\n\n## Laptop Keyboard Not Working on Windows 11\n\nIf your keyboard is not working on Windows 11, focus on these areas first.\n\n- Accessibility settings like Filter Keys\n- Language and keyboard layout settings\n- Windows Update\n- Device Manager driver update or reinstall\n- External keyboard test\n- [Full laptop test](/test/full) if you want to check more hardware in one flow\n\nWindows 11 users should also check whether the problem affects only one app or the whole system.\n\n## Laptop Keyboard Not Working on Windows 10\n\nIf your keyboard is not working on Windows 10, check these first.\n\n- Keyboard layout settings\n- Ease of Access keyboard settings\n- Device Manager driver update or reinstall\n- [Keyboard test](/test/keyboard)\n- External keyboard test\n- Restart after Windows updates\n\nMany Windows 10 keyboard problems are caused by layout changes, accessibility settings, or old drivers.\n\n## Laptop Keyboard Typing Wrong Letters or Symbols\n\nIf the keyboard is typing but the wrong letters appear, the keyboard may not be broken at all.\n\nThis problem is usually caused by:\n\n- Wrong keyboard layout\n- Wrong input language\n- Num Lock or function key behavior\n- Software settings inside a specific app\n\nCheck the layout first before trying hardware fixes.\n\n## Function Keys Not Working on Laptop\n\nIf the normal keys work but the top row does not, the issue may only affect the function keys.\n\nCheck for:\n\n- Fn key behavior\n- Keyboard hotkey mode\n- Laptop brand shortcut settings\n- App-specific shortcuts\n\nThis is different from a full keyboard failure.\n\n## When Your Laptop Keyboard May Have a Hardware Problem\n\nIf you tried all the fixes above and the laptop keyboard is still not working, the issue may be hardware-related.\n\n- The same keys never respond.\n- The keys feel damaged or pushed down.\n- The problem started after a spill or drop.\n- The built-in keyboard does not work, but an external keyboard works.\n- The keyboard has obvious wear or damage.\n\nAt that point, you may need a repair technician, keyboard replacement, or an external keyboard as a temporary solution.\n\n:::faq\nWhy is my laptop keyboard not working?\nYour laptop keyboard may not be working because of dust, driver issues, wrong layout settings, Filter Keys, recent updates, or physical damage.\n:::\n\n:::faq\nHow do I fix a laptop keyboard that is not typing?\nStart by restarting the laptop, running a keyboard test, cleaning the keys, checking layout settings, turning off Filter Keys, and reinstalling the keyboard driver.\n:::\n\n:::faq\nWhy are some laptop keys not working?\nSome laptop keys may stop working because of dirt, wear, stuck keys, or physical damage under those specific keys.\n:::\n\n:::faq\nWhy is my laptop keyboard typing wrong letters?\nThis is usually caused by the wrong keyboard layout or input language setting in Windows.\n:::\n\n:::faq\nWhat if my laptop keyboard is not working but an external keyboard works?\nThat usually means the built-in keyboard is the problem, not the full system. The issue may be damage, wear, or an internal keyboard fault.\n:::\n\n:::faq\nCan I test my laptop keyboard online?\nYes. You can use LaptopAnalyzer''s [keyboard test](/test/keyboard) to check which keys respond. If you want to test more than the keyboard, you can use the [full laptop test](/test/full) to run all checks in one flow.\n:::\n\n## Final Thoughts\n\nIf your laptop keyboard is not working, the problem is usually easier to fix than it looks. In many cases, restarting the laptop, testing the keyboard, cleaning the keys, checking settings, and reinstalling the driver will solve the issue.\n\nIf you have gone through every step and the keyboard still does not work, the issue may be hardware-related. In that case, using an external keyboard or getting the laptop checked may be the next step.',
  '4782788b-c395-4148-ad35-b7116c86e203',
  true,
  NOW(),
  NOW()
);